
1977: design a low-cost system to enter the market in 1978.

Specifications:
• 1 MHz 6502
• 4K DRAM (best price-per-bit; 450ns cycle)
• 4K BASIC ROM
• 2K Character ROM (fixed font)
• 32 x 24 Text display
• Programmable BG+FG colors for raster effects (2 of 8 colors)
• 64 x 48 Semigraphics in 8 colors (Upper 128; semigraphics override FG color)
• PSG: 8-bit Counter, square wave
• Tech: 74LS VDP+PSG

Position: fast-follow low cost machine for 1978
Point of Difference: color + sound; hi-res graphics; lower-case! (vs TRS-80, Apple II)
Target market: Home market, Word Processing, Education, Business?
TAM: 100,000 units? (these new home computers seem popular)
Strategy: low-cost base system + upsell: 4K RAM Cart, Data Recorder, Composite Monitor, Printer, ...


1978/1979: secure Japanese order 50K 16Kx1 DRAM chips

Two uses:
• Premium 16K RAM Cart (forward compatible with next machine)
• Baseline 16K memory for the next machine


1980: design a fast-follow for the 1981 market (VIC-20)

Specifications:
• 1 MHz 6502
• 16K DRAM (best price-per-bit; still 450ns cycle)
• 8K BASIC ROMs (6K BASIC + 2K character ROM)
• 32 x 24 Text display with Color RAM (16 colors; 1Kx4 SRAM, also a row buffer)
• User defineable charcters (128/1K or 256/2K modes)
• Text modes: 32x24 1-color per cell; 16x24 2-color per cell
• APA modes: 256x192/1bpp, 128x192/2bpp + line-double modes to save RAM
• APA modes use Color RAM to provide 1-2 colors per 8x8 cell
• Programmable BG+AUX colors for raster effects (2 of 16)
• Hardware smooth scrolling
• PSG: 3 x 10-bit square wave + 1 x noise (software ADSR)
• Tech: Gate Array VDP+PSG
• Backwards compatibility: possible (same chcarcter ROM + logic in the GA)

Position: fast-follow next gen machine for 1981
Point of Difference: fast HW scrolling, 4-color modes with 3 unique colors per cell (one a half-bright variant)
Target market: Home games market + Education to sell it to parents
Strategy: low-cost base system + upsell (again): 16K RAM Cart, Disk Drive, Modem?, others as before.



